Logistic Regression with Bayesian Inference

Evan Carey, created for BH Analytics

The General Linear Model

  • We can generalize the ordinary linear model to a more flexible framework
  • In regular regression the predictor variables are on the same scale as the outcome
  • We assume a normal distribution \[ E(X) = B_{0} + B_{1}*X_{1} + B_{2}*X_{2} + ... + B_{k}*X_{k} + e\]
  • A more general framework would be to allow some function to link the predictors to the outcome
  • This is called the link function and in normal regression it is identity
  • We can also consider different distributional families for the outcome
  • The combination of the link function and the distributional family is the general linear model

Logistic Regression

\[ln(\frac{P}{1-P}) = B_{0} + B_{1}*X_{1} + B_{2}*X_{2} + ... + B_{k}*X_{k}\]

  • In logistic regression we are modeling a binary process, so the outcome takes on 1 of 2 possible values
  • The distributional family we use is the binomial distribution, so we assume the outcome follows a binomial distribution
  • The main parameter of interest is \(p\), the probability of the outcome occurrence
  • We use a function called the logit function to link the additive predictor variables to the parameter \(p\)
  • Thus our predictor variables are on the logit scale, not on the outcome (\(p\)) scale!
  • Logistic regression results are often reported as odds ratios, although we do not have to do that

Logistic Regression

\[ln(\frac{P}{1-P}) = B_{0} + B_{1}*X_{1} + B_{2}*X_{2} + ... + B_{k}*X_{k}\]

  • What is our target of inference in this model?
  • Where is the error term?

Visualizing the distribution

  • We can visualize the binomial distribution for \(p=0.2\) with \(n=1000\) using code like the following:
x=1:100
y=dbinom(x,size = 100,prob=0.2)
library(ggplot2)
qplot(x,y,geom = 'line')

Question: Rewrite the above code to explore how this graph changes for different values of p.

Answer:

x=1:100
for (i in c(0.05,0.1,0.2,0.5,0.9, 0.95)){
  y=dbinom(x,size = 100,prob=i)
  print(qplot(x,y,geom = 'line',
              main=paste0('Binomial Distribution with P=',i)))
  }

The logit function

  • In normal regression, the x and y variables are on the same scale
## normal scale 
x = -10:10 
y = x 
plot(x,y)

The logit function

  • In logistic regression the x and y variables are related by the logit function
## normal scale 
## logit scale 
y=plogis(x) 
plot(x,y)

The logit function

  • Note we can use the plogis and qlogis functions to go from the predictors to the outcome or vice-versa
## Outcome p = 0.2 to the betas 
qlogis(.2) 
## [1] -1.386294
## Predictors (Beta) to the probability 
plogis(1) 
## [1] 0.7310586

The glm function

  • We use the stan_glm function for general linear models
  • We must specify the link function and the distribution
  • A variety of models can be fit in this family
  • Normal: link=identity, family=Gaussian
  • Logistic: link=logit, family=binomial
  • Poisson: link=log, family=poisson
  • Gamma: link=log, family=Gamma
  • check the help for family and glm for more details

Fit GLM Null Model

  • Lets fit an initial model with low as the outcome and age and smoke as predictors
  • What exactly are we modeling here? The expected value of what?

CHAINS = 4
SEED = 42

## Run Initial Null Model

                 data=birthwt,
                 family = binomial(link = "logit"),
                 chains=CHAINS, 
                 seed=SEED)

  • The intercept is the average of the output ( the 0/1). So as expected, in this null model we have estimated the overall event rate.

GLM and the posterior predictions

  • A quick commentary about the posterior in a logistic regression (and other GLMs). We now have to differentiate between some things when we say make prediction on the posterior. If we make predictions for the posterior, there are a few things we could do:
    • Make predictions of the actual outcome. In this case, the outcome is a zero or a one (binary outcome!). If we want that, we call the posterior_predict() function.
    • Make predictions about the conditional expectation of the outcome. In this case, we are making a prediction of the expected value of the outcome. In the case of the logistic regression, this corresponds to the prob of success. We can express this as p (a number between 0 and 1), or we can express this as the linear predictor (sum of the betas). This is exactly what we discussed at the start of the lecture. If we want p, we use posterior_epred(). If we want the sum of the betas, we use posterior_linpred().
# examine the posterior (for each parameter, estimated value)
head(as.data.frame(mod0))
##   (Intercept)
## 1  -0.7931594
## 2  -0.8117102
## 3  -0.8778923
## 4  -0.8635234
## 5  -0.7266023
## 6  -0.9335216
# posterior predictions of expected value on outcome scale (prob)
post1 <- 
  posterior_epred(mod0)
# posterior predictions of expected value on beta scale scale 
post2 <- 
  posterior_linpred(mod0)
# posterior predictions on outcome scale (this is zeros and ones)
post3 <- 
  posterior_predict(mod0)
  • Notice the differences in how we might summarize them:
### summarize expected probs
# collapse to vector first - currently there are
# 189 columns and 4000 rows. One column for each observation
# and one row for each posterior sample
# since it is an intercept only model, each column is the same
# in terms of the expectation - so we can collapse to a single vector. 
post1_vec <- as.vector(post1)
# graph the posterior probs
hist(post1_vec,breaks = 100)

# median
median(post1_vec)
## [1] 0.3114882
# 90% interval
quantile(post1_vec,probs = c(0.05,0.95))
##        5%       95% 
## 0.2597658 0.3652211
  • We estimate the median predicted probability to be 0.31, with a 90 percent uncertainty interval of (0.26,0.36).
### Summarize the outcome predictions (0/1)
# overall mean
mean(post3)
## [1] 0.3121124
# variability in the mean?
# Summarize each row (each row is one sample)
# the sample mean is the mean of each row, and we have 4000 samples. 
row_means <- 
  apply(post3,MARGIN = 1,mean)
# now may comments about this distribution of means!
# 90% interval and median
quantile(row_means,probs = c(0.05,0.5,0.95))
##        5%       50%       95% 
## 0.2380952 0.3121693 0.3915344
  • Notice we have a bit wider confidence interval here. Which one corresponds to the uncertainty interval around the estimated intercept?
# get posterior estimates for intercept, transform to p
quantile(plogis(as.data.frame(mod0)$`(Intercept)`),
         probs= c(0.05,0.5,0.95))
##        5%       50%       95% 
## 0.2597658 0.3114882 0.3652211
  • The first approach seems correct (assuming we want confidence intervals around the estimated sample mean)!
  • My interpretation of it is this:
    • If we want to understand uncertainty in the estimate of the intercept, we use the conditional expectation function posterior_epred() or posterior_linpred(). This answers the question - what is our estimate of p (the probability of a the outcome), and what is the uncertainty around that estimate? This will correspond to odds ratio when we add in other predictors.
    • If we want to understand uncertainty in an observed sample mean with sample size n=189, given the estimated model parameters, the second approach using posterior_predict() is correct.

Add additional predictors into the model

  • There are other variables in the model that may be predictive of the outcome of low birthweight. We add them into the model using the standard R formula like below.
## Model with only age
mod1 <- stan_glm(low ~ age, data = birthwt,
                 family = binomial(link = "logit"),
                 prior = normal(0,2.5),
                 prior_intercept = normal(0,10))

Making predictions from the model

  • We can make predictions from the model using either posterior_linpred(), which will make predictions of the mean on the either the scale of the betas or the outcome (p in this case).
summary(birthwt$age)

##   14.00   19.00   23.00   23.24   26.00   45.00
df1 <- data.frame(age=14:45)
# Generate estimates on the beta scale
pred1_beta <- 
  posterior_epred(mod1,
                  newdata = df1)
# Generate estimates transformed to the outcome scale (p)
pred1_p <- 
  posterior_epred(mod1,
                  newdata = df1)

Question: Can you figure out how to make a plot summarizing the variation in the estimated relationship between age and birthwt from this posterior distribution?

Answer to the plotting question

# Create graphical summary of results
df1$pred_50 <- apply(pred1_p,2,median)
df1$pred_25 <- apply(pred1_p,2,quantile,probs=0.25)
df1$pred_75 <- apply(pred1_p,2,quantile,probs=0.75)
birthwt$low_01 <- ifelse(birthwt$low == 'yes', 1, 0)
# Create a plot of the center and 75% density interval
ggplot(data=birthwt,aes(y=low_01,x=age)) +
  geom_jitter(alpha=0.3,height=0.02) + 
  geom_pointrange(color='red', alpha=0.3, data=df1,
                  aes(y=pred_50,ymin=pred_25,ymax=pred_75,x=age))

Model Comparisons

You can use the same leave-one-out cross-validation method here to compare the model fits using the loo package and function.

loo1 <- loo(mod1)
loo2 <- loo(mod2)
loo3 <- loo(mod3)
loo_compare(loo1,loo2,loo3)
##      elpd_diff se_diff
## mod3  0.0       0.0   
## mod1 -1.1       2.5   
## mod2 -1.5       2.2

Summarizing Uncertainty in Functions of Parameters

  • We often summarize the results of a logistic regression as the odds ratio. The odds ratio is defined as simply the exponentiated Beta for the corresponding parameter. How can we use the posterior distribution from the model we just fit to get estimates of the odds ratios instead of the

Question: How would you create a table of odds ratios and the associated confidence intervals for the smoke parameter?
Hint: We generate ORs by exponentiating the beta

  • Answer
## get posterior draws 
mod3_posterior <- as.data.frame(mod3)
mod3_posterior$smoke_OR <- exp(mod3_posterior$smokeyes)
quantile(mod3_posterior$smoke_OR, 
         probs=c(0.1, 0.5, 0.9))
